div.h1: Interrupt Enable/Disable Critical Section During Context Switch
div.p: Danger Window: nested timer interrupts mid-switch corrupt partially-saved state

g.text: DANGER SCENARIO Nested Interrupt Mid-Switch (IF=1 during switch)
Kernel Stack State at Each Phase
Guard Conditions What Must Be True

div.p: Red = Danger / hot path Green = Safe / correct Yellow = Warning / caution Blue = Data flow Purple = CPU hardware action Gray = Padding / unused / disabled
T=10ms PIT IRQ0 fires CPU asserts INTR CPU checks: EFLAGS.IF=1 accept interrupt CPU auto-pushes: SS, ESP, EFLAGS, CS, EIP kernel stack (via TSS.ESP0) CPL 30 transition loads IDT[32] handler address
isr_32 stub running (Ring 0) push 0 fake error code push 32 interrupt number jmp isr_common_stub pusha saves EAX..EDI (8 regs 4B = 32 bytes) EFLAGS.IF = 0 (interrupt gate cleared IF on entry)
interrupt_dispatch() timer_handler() scheduler_tick() tick_counter++ Finds next READY process (Process B) Sets oldREADY, newRUNNING Calls context_switch(procA, procB)

Process B resumes isr_common_stub return path (if B was previously preempted) pop gs/fs/es/ds popa add esp, 8 iretd pops EIP, CS=0x1B, EFLAGS (IF=1), ESP, SS=0x23 Process B runs in Ring 3 with interrupts enabled
Bug: sti called too early (before ESP swap) IF=1 while procA registers partially pushed but ESP not yet saved
Second timer IRQ fires mid-switch CPU reads TSS.ESP0 (still points to procA kernel stack top) Pushes EFLAGS/CS/EIP on top of partially-saved procA context

Nested scheduler_tick() runs Tries to save "current process" registers but stack is corrupted procAcontext.esp gets wrong value (offset by 1220 bytes) ESP swap writes garbage address into procBcontext.esp

Result: Non-deterministic triple-fault Next context_switch_asm ret jumps to garbage EIP Fault cascades: #GP #DF triple fault silent reboot Bug is timing-dependent: appears only at certain interrupt rates
User mode running EFLAGS.IF = 1 Interrupts enabled 0x00003202
Interrupt gate entry EFLAGS.IF 0 (hardware clears IF) Prevents nested interrupts automatically CPU: EFLAGS &= ~0x200

pushfd in context_switch_asm Saves EFLAGS with IF=0 onto procA stack Correct: procA will restore this on re-entry (procA re-enters via isr_common_stub which does iretd, restoring the original user EFLAGS with IF=1)
procB saved EFLAGS (from when B was last preempted) Must have IF=1 set during fabrication: *--stack = 0x00000202; bit 9 = IF If IF=0 here: procB runs forever, timer never fires, system freezes
popfd in context_switch_asm Restores procB's EFLAGS IF=1 re-enabled After this instruction, next IRQ can fire Only pop + ret remain safe window

g.text: Process A Kernel Stack (after pusha + pushfd)
Process B Kernel Stack (fabricated initial frame)

div.p: BEFORE entering context_switch_asm Interrupts already disabled (entered via interrupt gate, IF=0) CR3 updated to new process's page directory TSS.ESP0 updated to new process's kernel_stack_top current_process pointer updated

DURING ESP swap IF=0 no interrupt can fire between pushfd and popfd New process's context.esp is valid (non-zero, in kernel heap range) New stack has correct frame: EFLAGS, EBP, EDI, ESI, EBX, EIP in order

AFTER popfd (new process) EFLAGS.IF = 1 (from saved state; process runs with IRQs enabled) EBP, EDI, ESI, EBX correctly restored from new stack ret lands at valid EIP (first-time: entry_fn; subsequent: isr_common_stub path)

CRITICAL: EFLAGS.IF=0 in procA's saved state is correct procA was interrupted IF=0 on save procA will re-enter via isr_common_stub iretd restores original user EFLAGS (IF=1) Never manually force IF=1 in the pushfd'd EFLAGS on the kernel stack
CR3 procBpage_directory (phys addr) Address space switches to Process B's page tables TLB flush occurs (full CR3 reload)
TSS.ESP0 procBkernel_stack_top MUST happen before next interrupt Wrong value next IRQ corrupts Process B's kernel stack
[ESP+0 ] EFLAGS (IF=0) ESP here
[ESP+4 ] EBP = 0
[ESP+8 ] EDI
[ESP+12] ESI
[ESP+16] EBX
[ESP+20] return EIP (into isr_common_stub)
[ESP+24] old_ctx ptr (procA)
[ESP+28] new_ctx ptr (procB)
[ESP+0 ] EFLAGS = 0x00000202 (IF=1) ESP loaded here
[ESP+4 ] EBP = 0 (bottom of call chain)
[ESP+8 ] EDI = 0
[ESP+12] ESI = 0
[ESP+16] EBX = 0
[ESP+20] EIP = entry_function (fabricated)
push ebx push esi push edi push ebp pushfd 5 pushes onto Process A's kernel stack EFLAGS.IF = 0 here (still in interrupt, IF was cleared by gate)
mov [procAcontext.esp], esp Saves Process A's ESP (stack with all regs on it) Process A is now fully suspended
mov esp, [procBcontext.esp] THE IDENTITY SWAP ESP now points to Process B's kernel stack Before this: every push/pop = Process A's stack After this: every push/pop = Process B's stack
popfd restores Process B's EFLAGS EFLAGS.IF must be 1 in saved state or B runs forever with IRQs off pop ebp pop edi pop esi pop ebx ret pops Process B's saved EIP resumes B
